Explanation summary (why parameterized queries are safe)
- When you build a SQL statement by concatenating raw user input into the SQL text, malicious input can change the SQL's structure (add OR clauses, close strings, add comments, or append additional statements). That is the root cause of SQL injection.
- Parameterized queries (aka prepared statements or bound parameters) separate the SQL code from the data. The SQL statement is sent to the database with placeholders; the user-supplied values are sent separately and treated strictly as values—not as code—so they cannot alter SQL syntax or logic.
- Other recommended defenses: input validation (as a defense-in-depth), least privilege database accounts, escaping when parameterization isn't available, and using ORM frameworks or query builders that correctly handle parameters.

